{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558856/1945080301/0387.xml":{"full_text":"ARMY is probing\nK1LUNG OF NAZIS\nnVlD. Colo., Aug. 2. (U.R) A mil\ninvestigation was underway\nita.ry in the slaying of turee Nazi\ntuday rs of war by their Ameri\nprlS soldier guard as they worked\n.\u2018fa potato patch.\nlnot(icers at nearby Camp Car\nmlo prisoner of war mtern\n*\u00b0n\\ renter of which the Ovid\nis a branch, said Purple\ncsmP Wearer Pvt. Harold W. Gar\nH\u00a3aa Vnlumbus, ind., shot the men\n!jn.trdav when, he reported, they\ny !*ened to \u2018\u2022rush\" him.\nthr,rland wounded in the North\nGif.,n campaign, was guarding a\nA nf 15 German prisoners as\nC weeded potatoes. He report\nZ fired with unerring accuracy,\na crippling arm wound,\nSg the prisoners instantly.\nm.g victims were Identified as\nHelmut pfifferling and An\nCP\u2018Nauner. and Pvt. Hugo Quaas.\nSf.v were among approximate\ninn German war prisoners en\nLed in farm work in this area.\n8 The shooting occurred, the\n\u20181 Carson public relations of\nsaid on the secluded farm of\nAlbert Riehiel, Jr., as othr\nH\u201eU\u2018lg occurred, the Camp\nr, 5ong public relations office\nCa.\u2018 on the secluded farm of\nHulbert Riehiel, Jr., as ether\nmembers of the detail looked on\nrarland was quoted as explaining.\nG THe prisoners made threaten\ning remarks to me before I f-ed.\nt fired mv carbine at them when\nt looked like they were going to\nrJfaDt Gordon Randolph, Camp\nr arson public relations officer,\nsaid Garland probably would be\nheld in military custody pending\nan Army court martial. Rndolph\npointed out, however, that the In\ndiana soldier had a \u201cgood\" Army\nrecord and was a veteran Mili\ntary Policeman.\nMOSTLY CANADIAN\nThe great American P alls car\nries onlv about 6 per cent of the\nwater of the Niagara river. The\nct!,er 95 per cent goes over the\nCanadian Falls._\nEase Neuralgia With\nQuick-Acting \u201cBC\u201d\nUse quu;^-*^\ning \u201cBC\u201d Head\nache Powders\nwhen you want\nprompt relief\nfrom neuralgic\npain. \u201cBC\u201d also\nrelieves head\naches, muscular\naches and func\ntional periodic\nsizes. Use only as directed. Consult\na physician when pains persist.\nNew Orleans Flier Spends Six Days\n,0n Tiny Raft Without Food Or Water\nBy RICHARD G. HARRIS\nUnited Press War Correspondent\nOKINAWA, Aug. 1\u2014(U.R)\u2014Second\nLt. William R. Simpson, 25, former\nly of New Orleans and Miami, who\nbailed out of his stricken plane off\nthe China coast, spent six days\non a tiny raft without food or wa\nter, fighting off sharks, eating sea\ngull hearts and listening to\n\u201cstrange music.\u201d\nSimpson took off from an Okina\nwa base on July 18 to photograph\nairfields and harbor installations\nat Hangchow.\nOff the China coast his left en\ngine started cutting out and Simp\nson began calling a Dumbo rescue\nship. He got no answer. At 5,000\nfeet he tried to roll the plane\nover and bail out, but his airspeed\nwas too slow and he dropped to\n2,000 feet to get up enough speed\nto lay the plane over on its back.\nHe fell only part way out and\nsomehow got hung in the opening.\n\u201cThe chute just sort of strung\nout behind me instead of opening\nwith a snap,\u201d he said. \u201cI must\nhave had 14 hands because I was\nall over that thing in no time. I\njust got it open in time to make\ntwo swings when I hit the water.,\nI was unbuckling the harness as\nI hit. It was the busiest time of\nmy life.\u201d\nSimpson inflated his life raft and\nsettled down to drifting. The next\nday he fought off two sharks with\npaddles and decided to try for the\nChina coast. He paddled for 12\nhours. The wind and waves rose\nduring the night and he became\nseasick. His fishing kit and other\ngear were washed out. His water\nhad been lost at the beginning.\nHere are extracts from his diary:\nJuly 20: \u2018\u2018Wind is still strong.\nSaw a snake about six feet long\nwith brown diamond patches. I shot\na seagull and tried to eat some\nof the flesh. I ate the heart but\nthe rest would not go down. I am\ndetermined to stay alive. I had\nanother visiting shark and a few\nporpoise.\u201d\nJuly 21: (Third Day) \u201cThe sun\nis very hot. I am suffering from\nburned hands and face. Must be\ndelirious because I caught jpyself\ntalking to somone I thought was\nsitting on the other side of the\nraft.\u201d Simpson afterwards said he\nheard faint music which sounded\nlike a mixed chorus in the dis\ntance, and even recognized Bee\nthoven's \u201cGlory Be to God in Na\nture.\u201d\nOn the same day Simpson sight\ned two Marine privateers but they\nwere too far away to see his sig\nnals. He saw one flight of about\n30 B-29\u2019s pass five miles North\neast but the sun was obscured and\nhis signal mirror would not oper\nA little later five P-47\u2019s flew\nnear and he attracted their atten\ntion. Forty-five minutes after they\nflew down for a look Dumbo res\ncue planes appeared but were un\nable to land because of the rough\nwater. A plane dropped a \u00bb^r\nraft, however, and he climbed into\nat6.\nLater a B-29 came over and\ndropped a sloop slung beneath thl\nhuge aircraft. It was equipped with\neverything Simpson needed includ\ning a chart marked with the course\nto Okinawa. Simpson cleared the\ndeck but was unable to start the\nengine so he rigged a sail.\nOn July 23 his hands were so\nsore and stiff he was unable to\noperate the boat properly. He then\ntried to rig up a radio transmitter\nbut lost the aerial carrying ba\nloons and kits.\nThe next day Simpson was far\noff course and was hardly able to\nmove because of the stiffness and\nsoreness. It was then the Dumbo\nrescue plane again appeared and\ntook him aboard.\nSimpson\u2019s wife, formerly Sarah\nE. Strickland, lives in New Orleans.\nThey met while attending high\nschool in Miami where Simpson\u2019s\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. H. J. Simp\nson, live.\nBoy Scouts Resting\nAfter Maneuvers At\nLake Singletary\nRoy Scouts at Singletary Lake\ntoday were recuperating from all\nRight maneuvers in which the\ndesignated \u201cRed and Blue armies\u2019\nwere supposed to outwit each other\nin their attacks.\nC. W. Baker, Scout executive,\nsaid Thursday night that the two\nsummer camp armies would take\nup positions with two miles of\nterrain between them and would\nfirst attack separately and at\ndawn would attack simultaneously.\nThe summer camp, which open\ned on July 1, has numbered about\n450 scout-weeks through this week,\nand next Sunday will mark the\nbeginning of the final week.\nThe Executive board of the\nCouncil, which met at the lake\nlast week, inspected the camp for\nhealth and safety precautions, and\nfound complete compliance. The\nboard also made plans for en\nlarging the use of the lake next\nyear, through the acquisition of\nmore boating equipment. They\nrecommended that next year s ses\nsion last only five weeks, instead\nof six.\n-V\n500 RESCUED\nNEW ORLEANS, Aug. 2\u2014(U.R)\u2014\nMore than 500 victims of subma\nrine sinkings were rescued from\nthe Gulf of Mexico by Coast\nGuardsmen of the Eighth Naval\ndistrict during critical days ip the\ngulf, it was revealed today.\n40 Firms Represented\nAt Reconversion Meet\nRepresentatives from 40 firms\nin this area yesterday attended\na special meeting at the council\nchamber of the City Hall, which\nwas held by the Raleigh district\noffice of the War Production\nBoard to acquaint industries with\nthe reconversion policies of the\nWPB.\nSeveral private conferences were\nheld following the general session.\nWPB\u2019s policies for the balance\nof 1945 were outlined by Thomas\nJ. Love, district manager of the\nWPB, and John W. Fitz, priorities\nmanager, during the session, and\nsome concrete idea of the limited\nassistance which will be available\n:n 1946 was also given.\nSince during the past sixty days\na great many of the restrictive L\nand M orders of WPB have been\nrevoked and have appreciably\nchanged industrial procedure, the\nWPB deemed it advisable to hold\nspecial meetings throughout the\nstate to acquaint Industry w'ih\nWPB\u2019s reconversion policy and the\nchange in priorities methods which\nare now rapidly developing.\n-V\nProbably the record ride in the\nPony Express was made by Robert\nHaslam, known as \u201cPony Bob\",\nwho rode 120 miles in Nevada in\neight hours and ten minutes.\nELECTION ORDERED\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 2\nThe National Labor Relations\nBoard announced today it had\nordered an election among em\nployees of Mock, Judson, Voeh\nringer Company, Inc., of Greens\nboro, N. C., to determine whether\nH I I I lull iti i V .1. Ji .1. .1. .1. .Ti rf. .1. .ti\nthe American Federation of Ho\u00bbi*\nery Workers (CIO) should b\u00ab\ndesignated as their bargaining\nagent. The board stipulated that\nthe election be held within 30\ndays.\n-V\nBUY WAR BONDS AND STAMPS\nMALARIA\nCHECKED IN 7 DAYS WITH\nLIQUID for\nA 4 MALARIAL\nA^ A^ Am SYMPTOMS\nIf H II II Take only as\n^W ^W directed\nEFFICIENT SEEING\nNothing is more valuable than clear, comfortable and efficient\nvision.\nNothing is more expensive than a pair of glasses bought at a\nprice, but without the additional services needed to produce J\nthe above desired results.\nNO PATIENT DISMISSED UNTIL VISUALLY COMFORTABLE\nDR. MIKE J. PALMER il\ni ii\nd^)ptontetnst\n2nd Floor Willetts Bldg., 120 Princess St. Phone 4004\n11 I 1\nV Don* ENDANGER^\nf Your HEALTH f\nI ^OSQUITOES orid FLIES\\\nW^CARRY GERMS^M\n[FLY-TOf\n1 Kills Em Dead i\n^AT DEALERS EVERYWHERE k\nFOX'S ROYAL BAKERY presents\u2014\nil\u2014,-_---\u25a0\u2014.\u2014\u2014 \u2014ji\nI'M -ALWAV5\ntacginlaftei?\ntow- so\nvwll all;.\nS\u00a3E A LOT i\nOF ME/ 1\nv ri\n,T^I5 15 MV 5ISTH?\nSl/ZY- ANP FDR I\nA GIRL SHE'S A\nGOOD SPP^T,\nVC A\u00ab\u00a3 POING A Bic JOB\nOF NEIGHBORHOOD SCRAP \\KD\nPAPER COLLECTINGWE ASK\nEvEpyeopy on ooa street\nTO SAVE THEIR WASTE\nPAPER top\nos\n\\JHD WOULD EVETA'\nWINK WASHIN6/y\nDI5H\u00a35 WAS WAR\nWORK BUT MOMjl\nyrs S02y Mor\\\n1 COULDM'T CO 10\nTHAT REP CP05S